<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-09-02T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-09-02T00:00:00-05:00" n="800" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d800">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 841.731/2</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_PWH1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Page</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <dateline>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="italic">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-09-02">
                                <hi rend="italic">September 2, 1914</hi>.</date>
                            <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 8:30 p.m.</hi>] </dateline>
                        <p rend="center">[Telegram]</p>
                        <p>558. Your telegram of August 23, 8 p.m. The Foreign Office now informs me
                            that there is nothing in the censorship regulations to prevent the
                            correction of errors made in transmission in the usual manner provided
                            for in the international telegraph regulations. If the matter is to be
                            taken up further the telegraph company must give particular instances in
                            which censors are alleged to have refused to pass service messages for
                            such correction.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Ambassador</hi>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>